According to Jan's Indeoe2 opisthotonus occurs in Pliny 24 times, tetanus 9 times, and emprosihotonus not at all. According to the same Index, dyspnoea is mentioned 4 times, asthma twice, orthopnoea 28 times, and suspiriosi (not apparently in Celsus) 34 times.

The first reaction of a reader is to infer that Pliny was lax in his use of these terms, as Celsus says some people were in their use of the terms for the various forms of tetanus. But Pliny is not an original authority3 he is merely a note-takes, borrowing his technical terms from other writers, whether Greek or Roman. The laxity (if laxity there is) is not Pliny’s⁷ but that of his sources. It is possible that suspiriosus is a word which was in general use, and not a technical term of the physicians.
